        {
          "type": "figure",
          "id": "fig-ch05_03_03",
          "caption": {
            "segmentId": "m66375:caption:fig-ch05_03_03-caption"
          },
          "media": {
            "id": "fs-id2013541",
            "alt": "This illustration shows the sodium-potassium pump. Initially, the pumps opening faces the cytoplasm, where three sodium ions bind to it. The antiporter hydrolyzes an A T P to A D P and, as a result, undergoes a conformational change. The sodium ions are released into the extracellular space. Two potassium ions from the extracellular space now bind the antiporter, which changes conformation again, releasing the potassium ions into the cytoplasm.",
            "src": "../../media/Figure_05_03_03-62aa.jpg",
            "mimeType": "image/jpg"
          }
        },
