        {
          "type": "figure",
          "id": "fig-ch05_03_04",
          "caption": {
            "segmentId": "m66375:caption:fig-ch05_03_04-caption"
          },
          "media": {
            "id": "fs-id2078828",
            "alt": "This illustration shows a membrane bilayer with two integral membrane proteins embedded in it. The first, a sodium-potassium pump, uses energy from A T P hydrolysis to pump three sodium ions out of the cell for every two potassium ions it pumps into the cell. The result is a high concentration of sodium outside the cell and a high concentration of potassium inside the cell. There is also a low concentration of glucose outside the cell, and a high concentration inside. A sodium-amino acid co-transporter simultaneously transports sodium and the glucose into the cell. Text within the image reads as follows: Primary Active Transport: the sodium potassium pump moves sodium ions using the energy of ATP hydrolysis to establish a concentration gradient of sodium ions. Secondary active transport: Sodium ions moving with the concentration gradient established by the sodium potassium pump drives the transport of glucose against its concentration gradient.",
            "src": "../../media/Figure_05_03_04-851f.png",
            "mimeType": "image/jpg"
          }
        }
      ]
    },
